<chapter id="kfilereplace-features">
 <title>&kfilereplace; features</title>
 <para>
  This chapter provides informations about some usefull capabilities of &kfilereplace;.
 </para>
 <sect1 id="kfilereplace-the-kfr-file">
  <title>How to save your string list</title>
  <para>
    When you want to reuse a list of strings you can save it in a xml file. To do this select from the menu bar "Search/Replace | Strings | Save Strings List to File" option. When you save a list, a simple xml file with extension "kfr" is created. To load an kfr file select from menu bar "Search/Replace | Strings | Load Strings List from File". The actual format of this file is:
   <screenshot>
     <screeninfo>Here's a screenshot of &kfilereplace;</screeninfo>
     <mediaobject>
       <imageobject>
         <imagedata fileref="kfr_format.png" format="PNG"/>
       </imageobject>
       <imageobject>
         <imagedata fileref="kfr_format.eps" format="EPS"/>
       </imageobject>
       <textobject>
         <phrase>Screenshot</phrase>
       </textobject>
     </mediaobject>
     </screenshot>
  </para>
  <para>
   if you are using a previous format you can update by hand your file by simply according it to the above scheme. In alternative you can load the file written in the old format and save it again with &kfilereplace; in the way we explained before.
  </para>
</sect1>
<sect1 id="kfilereplace-the-report-file">
  <title>How to create a simple report</title>
  <para>
   You can create a report by choosing "Search/Replace | Results | Create Report File" from the menu. A report is a directory containing an xml file and a css file. Reports may be usefull to maintain a simple log system of your operations. Look at the picture.
    <screenshot>
      <screeninfo>Here's a screenshot of &kfilereplace;</screeninfo>
      <mediaobject>
	<imageobject>
	  <imagedata fileref="report_example.png" format="PNG"/>
	</imageobject>
	<imageobject>
	  <imagedata fileref="report_example.eps" format="EPS"/>
	</imageobject>
	<textobject>
	  <phrase>Screenshot</phrase>
	</textobject>
      </mediaobject>
    </screenshot>
  </para>
</sect1>
<sect1 id="kfilereplace-QT-regexp">
 <title>How to use regular expressions</title>
  <para>
    If you want search for every string that starts with "x" or "ht" or "u" and ends with "ml" you can write a regular expression like this "(x|ht|u)ml". Insert this expression in the search editor, click Ok button, and finally enable regular expressions by toggling the <link linkend="kfilereplace-the-toolbar">regexp button</link>. Please note that using regular expressions lets you to make very complicated search, but the cost could be a speed performance degradation.
  </para>
</sect1>
<sect1 id="kfilereplace-backup-file">
  <title>How to protect original files</title>
  <para>
    If you don't want to lose your original files, you can do a copy of them before the replacing the strings. You only must insert your strings, and before starting replace you must toggle the <link linkend="kfilereplace-the-toolbar">backup button</link>. If you want to customize the extension of the backup files open the <link linkend="kfilereplace-the-options-dialog">option dialog</link>.
  </para>
</sect1>
<sect1 id="kfilereplace-open-file">
  <title>How to open a file</title>
  <para>
   If you want to open a file that matches some of your strings, you must select a line in the result view and click with the right button of the mouse. A menu will appear, then you only have to choose a option on it. Note that if you use &kfilereplace; embedded in Quanta+ you can open the file directly on it at the specified line and column.
  </para>
</sect1>
<sect1 id="kfilereplace-commands">
 <title>Commands</title>
  <para>
    Suppose you want subtitute the phrase "Alice's adventures in wonderland" with the entire file that contains Carroll's novel. Probably you don't want to do this by hand, what you need is a "command" that do it for you. So click the <link linkend="kfilereplace-the-toolbar">add</link> button, select "search and replace mode" and insert the following strings: "Alice's adventure in wonderland" in the search mini editor and the string <quote>[$loadfile:/the-path-to-my-directory/my-directory/my-file$]</quote> in the replace mini editor. Click Ok button, and when you come back to &kfilereplace; main window, toggle the <link linkend="kfilereplace-the-toolbar">command action</link> button that enables the commands, and start the replace. Other commands are presents, please see <link linkend="available-commands">Appendix B</link> for a list of available commands.
  </para>
</sect1>
</chapter>

